---
import ActBreak from '../ActBreak.astro';
import FigurePlate from '../FigurePlate.astro';
---

<ActBreak
  roman="Act III"
  title="A Lab That Can't"
  accent="Fool Itself"
  tease="Bold claims need a boring machine: pre-registered bets, double gates, and adversaries hunting for errors."
  id="act-3"
/>

<section class="section-divider" id="architecture">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">05</span> The method</div>
    <h2>How do you trust results like these?</h2>

    <p>
      A thousand-year-old philosophy steering an AI — the claim invites skepticism, and it should.
      So before any experiment ran, the project built something rarer than the result:
      a lab designed so that <strong>wishful thinking cannot survive it</strong>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Three habits do the work. First, every experiment is a <strong>sealed bet</strong>: seeds,
      commands, and pass criteria are committed to the public record <em>before</em> the run —
      no re-rolling, no quiet goalpost moves. Second, no claim closes without
      <strong>two independent gates</strong>: the code must pass its tests <em>and</em> the
      pre-registered scientific criterion must be met. Passing tests alone never closed anything.
      Third, eighteen <strong>adversarial reviews</strong> — reviewers shown only the evidence
      files, never the narrative — forced documented corrections, including downgrading one of the
      project's own favourite claims.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_architecture"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 2"
      alt="Three-tier system diagram: frozen model with reader and writer, the five rules as controller, and the automated research loop"
      caption="The full stack, as drawn in the paper. Bottom: a frozen language model (no weights are ever updated, anywhere in this project) with the lens-based writer and reader attached. Middle: the five rules acting as controller. Top: the automated loop that chose which experiment to fund next."
      gates={["gates/*.json", "efe_ledger.jsonl"]}
    />

    <div class="stat-strip">
      <div class="card card-teal"><div class="stat-big">130</div><div class="stat-label">public evidence records ("gates")</div></div>
      <div class="card card-teal"><div class="stat-big">27</div><div class="stat-label">experiment cycles, machine-selected</div></div>
      <div class="card card-teal"><div class="stat-big">18</div><div class="stat-label">adversarial reviews with forced corrections</div></div>
      <div class="card card-teal"><div class="stat-big">8</div><div class="stat-label">frozen models, 5 families</div></div>
    </div>

    <details class="expand">
      <summary>For researchers: who chose the experiments?</summary>
      <div class="expand-body">
        <p>
          Experiment selection was delegated to an <strong>expected-free-energy selector</strong>
          over registered menus — the explore/exploit calculus of active inference, here choosing
          which loop to fund next by expected information gain against cost. Its ledger is public:
          267 observation events, 41 proposals, 27 spend entries, 9 menus. This is the same
          machinery behind the companion project,
          <a href="https://sharathsphd.github.io/ActiveCIrcuitDiscovery/">Active Circuit Discovery</a> —
          there it chose interpretability experiments; here it ran a research programme.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section-divider" id="compute" style="padding-top:0;">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">06</span> The bill</div>
    <h2>The whole programme cost eighteen GPU-hours</h2>

    <p>
      One number worth sitting with. The entire registered programme — every replication, every
      seed, every negative result you'll meet in Act V — consumed
      <strong>18.17 GPU-hours</strong> on one shared machine. Not a datacenter. Roughly a
      weekend of compute, spent the way a careful gambler spends chips: each experiment scored
      beforehand by what it could teach against what it would cost, and no experiment ever re-run
      to fish for a prettier answer.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_compute"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 3"
      alt="Per-loop GPU-hours as bars with a cumulative total line"
      caption="The compute ledger, loop by loop. Bars: per-loop GPU-hours; line: cumulative total (18.17 h through the budgeted programme; 19.02 h including the later benchmark loop). The single largest item is the 27-billion-parameter replication (6.1 h)."
      gates={["research/state.json"]}
    />

    <p>
      With the lab established, we can finally ask the question you came here for:
      <em>does any of this actually work?</em>
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
